<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911220-0059</DOCNO><DOCID>911220-0059.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- RJR Nabisco Holdings:   New Bank Credit Facility   Will Reduce Interest Costs</HL><DATE>12/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C20</SO><CO>   RN</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS AND SERVICES (HOU)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS (HPR)TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)</IN><NS>FINANCING AGREEMENTS (FNC)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp., New York, said it completed anew bank credit facility that reduces its interest costs bymore than two percentage points.   The holding company for food and tobacco giant RJR NabiscoInc. said the new agreement makes available a $6.5 billionline of credit. The cheaper bank borrowing is part of astrategy undertaken by the company since its 1989 leveragedbuy-out to rebuild its balance sheet through several equitytransactions and debt restructurings. Earlier this month, RJRNabisco received an investment-grade rating for some of itsbonds, the first such rating since the buy-out.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;We've been very aggressive retiring debt and addingequity over the last 18 months,&quot; said Louis V. Gerstner Jr.,chairman and chief executive. &quot;With the new bank agreement,RJR Nabisco is removed from the bank regulators' list ofhighly leveraged transactions.&quot;   Mr. Gerstner said the company's debt would total $14.4billion at year end, and total equity would be $8.4 billion.At the time of the company's buy-out, RJR Nabisco had debt ofmore than $29 billion and $1.5 billion of equity.</TEXT></DOC>